        "trailText":"Sky Lantern seemed an unlikely runner and Soft Falling Rain may drop out after Ascot turned soft before Champions Day",
        "headline":"Ascot goes soft as Soft Falling Rain's trainer mulls Champions Day run",
        "body":"<p>The going at Ascot turned soft all round on Wednesday after a midday downpour dropped 6mm of rain on the course. That news will be unwelcome for a number of trainers who would like to have Champions Day runners at the Berkshire track on Saturday, but are unhappy about the prospect of a testing surface.</p><p>The first Champions Day, in 2011, was blessed with fine weather and good going but there was a feeling at the time that it would not normally be the case for a mid-October fixture. This will be the second time running that the card, offering £3.4m in prize money, will be held on a surface with plenty of give.</p><p>Asked to predict the likely going for Saturday, Chris Stickels, Ascot's clerk of the course, said: \"I think it'll be a mixture of good to soft and soft.\"</p><p>He reported a forecast predicting \"occasional showers\" for Thursday, Friday and Saturday but added: \"It's hit and miss stuff, very difficult to predict how much we're likely to get, but I would say [Thursday] is quite likely to be dry. It's an unclear picture after that. I think we've seen the worst of it.\"</p><p>Soft Falling Rain is, ironically, one of the horses whose connections would rather see plenty of sun in the Ascot area. A Group One winner in his native South Africa, he was a comfortable winner on fast ground at Newmarket last month, on the strength of which he is joint second-favourite for Saturday's QEII Stakes, worth £1m.</p><p>While that prize money is plainly tempting, Soft Falling Rain could yet be withdrawn, should his trainer, Mike de Kock, decide the ground is too testing. \"If it becomes a bog, Mike has said that he'll have to talk it over with [the colt's owner] Sheikh Hamdan,\" said Steve Jell, De Kock's assistant trainer. \"So we're training him for the race but we'll have to keep an eye on the weather, just as a lot of other people are doing.</p><p>\"He's such a good-actioned horse on fast, firm ground. Will he be effective on both [types of going]? We're not too sure.\"</p><p>Jell takes some comfort from the fact that the QEII is due to be run up Ascot's straight mile, which drains more quickly than the round course. He reported a lot of enthusiasm within the camp for Soft Falling Rain's chance. \"He upped his game in quite an impressive manner last time,\" Jell said. \"He's got to do that again but he's a fighter who doesn't give up easily.\"</p><p>De Kock is also due to run Igugu in the Fillies &amp; Mares Stakes, newly raised to Group One status, and Jell hopes that, as a daughter of Galileo, she will be able to cope with some cut underfoot. Igugu has not been able to reproduce her best form since leaving South Africa last year, which Jell explained was in part because she had not enjoyed her experiences of travel, but he added that she was showing signs of coming back to herself after five months in Newmarket.</p><p>There appears to be confusion in the Sky Lantern camp over whether the grey will run on Champions Day, with her trainer, Richard Hannon, appearing to rule it out just one day after his son and assistant, Richard Jr, had enthused about her chance of running in quotes reported by the Racing Post. Her jockey, Richard Hughes, used the Hannon website yesterday to say: \"I'd be inclined to give it a miss … It would not surprise me if it rode heavy.\"</p><p>Hughes revealed that the Hannon-trained Olympic Glory will wear blinkers for the first time when he runs in the QEII. \"We gave him&nbsp;a spin in them earlier in the week and there was a positive reaction. I would envisage it could make three lengths difference, which would put him in&nbsp;there with a big shout,\" the jockey said.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420181668|2013-10-17T12:52:59Z|0b35d096665d799d726ca34a87dc6ddc35ec7b8c -->",
