        "headline":"Talking Horses: A perfect storm for Lingfield punters, plus best bets",
        "body":"<h2>Today's best bets, by Chris Cook<br /></h2><p>A perfect storm is forecast to hit punters at Lingfield late this afternoon, when Cafe Society runs. Here are the close-up comments for the colt's last two starts, both at Ascot. As you read them, bear in mind that he is now switching to Leafy, where every finish comes with guaranteed heartbreak for someone:</p><p><strong>13 July</strong> 2nd of eight, beaten a neck</p><p><em>Steadied start, held up in last, smooth progress on inner just over 2f out to track leading trio over 1f out, switched around them soon after, pushed along and closed to take 2nd last stride, too much to do</em></p><p><strong>7 September</strong> 5th of 14, beaten two and a quarter lengths</p><p><em>Heavily restrained start, held up in last, ridden 2f out, stayed on from over 1f out to take 5th last strides, far too much to do </em></p><p>Jamie Spencer, who rode in the July race, is back aboard, Martin Lane having ridden him the last time. Connections appear to believe the horse must be held up, in which case he'll always need a strong pace and luck in running.</p><p>He might get both today but would you enjoy betting on that at the available odds of 13-8? I'd rather take <strong>Space Ship (4.05)</strong> at 7-2, even though you face some of the same risks with him. This counts as a step down in class for a horse who was beaten only a length in the King George V at Royal Ascot and the vibes appear positive for this John Gosden beast, returning from a three-month break.</p><p>Soft going at Nottingham is likely to mean the finishes look very different to those at Lingfield. I fancy a couple of Tom Queally's mounts and, although he's not a jockey I follow, I'm interested to note that he has ridden more winners at this track in the past five years than any of his colleagues with mounts in the relevant races.</p><p><strong>Weapon Of Choice (4.20)</strong> is up 5lb for scoring at Epsom a fortnight ago, which counted as a return to form after 18 winless months. He had looked very unlucky on his previous start at Newbury, even though only ninth. He remains well treated on his best form and has conditions to suit, so 10-1 is enticing.</p><p>In the closing sprint handicap, <strong>Pastureyes (5.50)</strong> is friendless at 25-1 on Betfair but has an interesting profile. She showed some promise in maidens and then won on her handicap debut, despite appearing to hate Brighton. She was drawn away from the main action at Leicester next time and may have disliked the fast ground, finishing well beaten. With first-time cheekpieces and Queally replacing a 5lb claimer, it appears connections mean business, though soft ground is an unknown.</p><p>Another runner who may be overpriced is <strong>Diamond Frontier (2.50) </strong>at 14-1 for the two-mile handicap chase at Wetherby. He will need to be fit for this reappearance but John Wade's horses have been winning at a 16% strike-rate since the new season began in May and several have been at big prices — the market does not seem to offer reliable insights into the chances of runners from this yard.</p><h2>Tipping competition, day three<br /></h2><p>Our winners so far:</p><p><strong>Monday</strong></p><p>Hasopop 7-2</p><p>Layla's Oasis 22-1</p><p>Eric The Grey 11-1</p><p><strong>Tuesday</strong></p><p>Embsay Crag 10-1</p><p>Dom Lukka 5-2</p><p>Ty Gwr 12-1</p><p>And our leader is:</p><p><strong>Tommy2002</strong> +32.50</p><p>… who added Embsay Crag to Hasopop and Layla's Oasis for a deeply impressive start. Even so, he is barely ahead of <strong>15244</strong> (+30) and <strong>ID3220887</strong> (+28).</p><p>Today, we'd like your selections, please, for these races: <strong>3.55 Wetherby</strong>, <strong>4.20 Nottingham</strong>, <strong>5.10 Lingfield</strong>.</p><p>In the event of a tie at the end of the week, the winner will be the tipster who, from among those tied on the highest score, posted their tips earliest on the final day.</p><p>This week's prize is a copy of <strong>Timeform's Chasers &amp; Hurdlers</strong> annual, the much-loved and lovingly produced book which serves as a complete record of the last jumps season (and, hopefully, offers some insights into the new one). Costing £75 if you actually pay for it, the latest annual is newly published and will shortly be reviewed on this site by m'colleague Tony Paley. You can <a href=\"http://www.timeform.com/show_article.asp?num=73\" title=\"Timeform\">buy a copy here</a> or <a href=\"http://v.calameo.com/2.0/cviewer.swf?bkcode=000362465232732dfe24c&amp;langid=en\" title=\"Calameo\">read a sample here</a>.</p><p>As ever, our champion will be the tipster who returns the best profit to notional level stakes of £1 at starting price on our nominated races, of which there will be three each day up until Friday. Non-runners count as losers.</p><p>If you have not already joined in this week, you can do so today, but you will start on -6.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2009/sep/07/talking-horses-tipping-competition-terms-and-conditions\" title=\"Ts  Cs\">For terms and conditions click here</a>.</p><p>Good luck!</p><p>Click <a href=\"http://guardian.sportinglife.com/GU_Meetings\" title=\"racecards\">here for all the day's racecards</a>, form, stats and results.</p><p><em>And post your tips or racing-related comments below.</em></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420133344|2013-10-17T12:52:59Z|e98259fe7a756236f1054df9e582b577afb979b7 -->",
