        "trailText":"<p><strong>Chris Cook: </strong>The £2.5m colt Hydrogen is expected to make a belated racecourse debut a week on Saturday, plus best bets for today</p>",
        "headline":"Talking Horses: News of Hydrogen's debut and best bets for today",
        "body":"<h2>Today's best bets, by Chris Cook<br /></h2><p>Remember Hydrogen? Just over a year ago, he made headlines when sold at Tattersalls in Newmarket for 2.5m guineas to Sheikh Fahad, who was enticed by the prospect of owning a Galileo half-brother to Authorized.</p><p>There then followed <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2012/oct/14/hydrogen-colt-newmarket-sales\" title=\"Guardian report\">an amusing arrangement</a> by which the Sheikh's 20 British trainers were gathered together for lunch and presented with envelopes containing the details of which yearlings would be sent to them. One of those lucky trainers would find Hydrogen's name staring up at them.</p><p>Of course, the glass-half-empty view is that it's a curse to be sent such a high-profile prospect. If he does well, it's because of his innate talent; if he flops, it's because you're a loser.</p><p>Anyway, the lot fell on Peter Chapple-Hyam, who has presumably spent much of the year worrying about what the British Horseracing Authority were going to do to him (he had doctored some phone records when asked to produce them). <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/sep/05/peter-chapple-hyam-fine-phone-records\" title=\"Guardian report\">In the event, he was fined £5,000</a>, which must have been at the lower end of the punishments the trainer had envisaged for himself.</p><p>Only Chapple-Hyam can say whether that distraction has had any impact on his productivity this season but, for whatever reason, he has managed just 11 winners so far at an 8% strike-rate, compared to 29 at 16% through the whole of 2012. And, of course, we have yet to see Hydrogen on a racecourse, with almost all the major juvenile races now behind us.</p><p>But word has come from Sheikh Fahad's racing manager, David Redvers, that the colt is being lined up for a Newbury maiden a week on Saturday, one week before the end of turf racing in Britain. \"I saw him do another piece of work the other morning under Jamie Spencer and he worked with a very fast lead-horse and went extremely well,\" Redvers told Sky Sports News Radio.</p><p>\"He looks a nice mile-and-a-half horse, which is what you'd expect on pedigree. We'd just like to get him to win a maiden and put him away for the winter.</p><p>\"He's certainly showing that he's way above average ability. I think he'll turn into a beautiful three-year-old.\"</p><p>Just to confirm that acquiring an expensive yearling is only the start of a trainer's problems, consider Classic Devotion, sold for $1.2m at Saratoga in August last year and not seen since. Now with Godolphin's Charlie Appleby, he was due to make a belated and low-key racecourse debut today at Newcastle but has been pulled out.</p><p>That, presumably, is because the going is now heavy in places after 31mm of rain since declarations were made on Sunday. Classic Devotion is a son of Street Cry, whose progeny have a 5% strike-rate on heavy and only a 7% strike-rate on soft. His only other entry at the moment is in the Derby and the odds are good that we won't see him until next year.</p><p><strong>Authentication (4.00)</strong> should love the ground, though, as a son of Authorized, whose kids score at a 24% rate on heavy (13/55 so far). He has already contributed to that tally, having scored on deep ground at Folkestone last year, when with Mark Johnston. Mel Brittain hasn't had much joy out of him yet but the horse hasn't really had his ground yet and is now back down to 1lb above his last winning mark. I like him at 16-1.</p><p>The day's nap is <strong>Trixie Malone (5.30)</strong>, who gave Karl Burke one of his first winners after recovering his licence when scoring on her handicap debut at Ayr last month. She and Mash Potato pulled clear of their rivals that day and I'd bet a 6lb rise underestimates her.</p><p>That was her first run for four months and her first on soft, so she should be ready to go well again in these conditions. At 4-1, the market sees her chance but I still think those odds are a bit generous.</p><p>At Huntingdon, I'm interested in a couple of horses who were showing improved form when they fell last time. <strong>Darnborough (2.50) </strong>was four lengths up over today's course and distance when coming down at the last a month ago, while <strong>Lucky To Be Alive (4.20) </strong>tripped over the second-last at Uttoxeter when disputing the lead. I think there are good reasons to expect continued progress from both and they appeal at 5-1 and 7-1 respectively.</p><h2>Tipping competition, day two<br /></h2><p>Our winners so far:</p><p><strong>Monday</strong></p><p>Hasopop 7-2</p><p>Layla's Oasis 22-1</p><p>Eric The Grey 11-1</p><p>And our leader is:</p><p><strong>Tommy2002</strong> +24.50</p><p>… who made a scarcely believable start with both Hasopop and Layla's Oasis.</p><p>Today, we'd like your selections, please, for these races: <strong>4.00 Newcastle</strong>, <strong>4.20 Huntingdon</strong>, <strong>5.45 Leicester</strong>.</p><p>In the event of a tie at the end of the week, the winner will be the tipster who, from among those tied on the highest score, posted their tips earliest on the final day.</p><p>This week's prize is a copy of <strong>Timeform's Chasers &amp; Hurdlers</strong> annual, the much-loved and lovingly produced book which serves as a complete record of the last jumps season (and, hopefully, offers some insights into the new one). Costing £75 if you actually pay for it, the latest annual is newly published and will shortly be reviewed on this site by m'colleague Tony Paley. <a href=\"http://www.timeform.com/show_article.asp?num=73\" title=\"Timeform\">You can buy a copy here</a> or <a href=\"http://v.calameo.com/2.0/cviewer.swf?bkcode=000362465232732dfe24c&amp;langid=en\" title=\"Calameo\">read a sample here</a>.</p><p>As ever, our champion will be the tipster who returns the best profit to notional level stakes of £1 at starting price on our nominated races, of which there will be three each day up until Friday. Non-runners count as losers.</p><p>If you have not already joined in this week, you can do so today, but you will start on -3.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2009/sep/07/talking-horses-tipping-competition-terms-and-conditions\" title=\"Ts  Cs\">For terms and conditions click here</a>.</p><p>Good luck!</p><p>Click <a href=\"http://guardian.sportinglife.com/GU_Meetings\" title=\"racecards\">here for all the day's racecards</a>, form, stats and results.</p><p><em>And post your tips or racing-related comments below.</em></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420021683|2013-10-17T12:52:59Z|69960291b0417e2ece874be3c4abedbf7498db32 -->",
