      "sectionId":"sport",
      "sectionName":"Sport",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-15T10:47:23Z",
      "webTitle":"'Plastic' Grand National at risk of becoming a parody, says Timeform",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/oct/15/plastic-grand-national-parody-timeform",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2013/oct/15/plastic-grand-national-parody-timeform",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"The latest edition of Timeform's Chasers &amp; Hurdlers annual warns against further changes to the Grand National course",
        "headline":"'Plastic' Grand National at risk of becoming a parody, says Timeform",
        "body":"<p>The latest running of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/apr/06/auroras-encore-grand-national-horses-fell\" title=\"Guardian report\">the world's most famous race</a>, the first to ditch the traditional timber-framed fences in favour of \"more forgiving\" obstacles made partly of synthetic birch, might become known in future years as the first \"plastic Grand National\", warn racehorse ratings experts at Timeform.</p><p></p><p>\"The latest National field was still intact approaching the eighth fence, the Canal Turn, a situation unprecedented in the long history of the race, and the changes to the fences seemed to compromise the challenge of the race which has always been regarded as 'the supreme test of jumping,'\" argues Timeform.</p><p></p><p>\"The Grand National engenders strong feelings amongst its opponents, but it is the biggest prize in jumping, with a rich and colourful history, and the authorities must be wary of making changes that risk turning the race into a parody or imitation of itself,\" it concludes.</p><p></p><p>The comment comes in a wide-ranging essay on the National winner Auroras Encore in the organisation's latest Chasers &amp; Hurdlers annual, out this week, in which it argues: \"Maintaining the essence of the race revolves around striking the right balance between the tradition of providing the ultimate challenge and the risks that the participants face, and also preserving the spectacle of the race.\"</p><p></p><p>Timeform lists the tinkering that has taken place with the National in recent years and, while making it clear that it is wholly opposed to any further alterations, points out that \"no one should be under any illusion that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/mar/25/rspca-bechers-brook-may-have-to-go\" title=\"Guardian story\">to appease the RSPCA, for example, even more changes will have to be made\"</a>.</p><p></p><p>If there is a \"tinkerman\" in British racing it is Phil Smith, the British Horseracing Authority's head of handicapping, who introduced a significant new development when he decided to start giving the top weights in the National a distinct advantage in order to attract a higher quality of runner.</p><p></p><p>It is an alteration, which Timeform is very much opposed to. In its essay on Tidal Bay, who would have raced off a mark 9lb lower than in handicaps away from Aintree, if he had not been injured prior to the National, it states: \"The BHA handicappers have the discretion to treat some of the Grand National top weights relatively leniently, a policy that has always been hard to justify yet seems to go unquestioned.</p><p></p><p>\"The Grand National is far and away the most valuable race in the jumping calendar in Britain and Ireland, and in truth, the owners of the best chasers shouldn't need any more incentive than that.\"</p><p></p><p>Whether the lack of high-profile opposition among, for example, trainers will remain the case if one of the top-rated horses given preferential treatment wins is another matter.</p><p></p><p>It is safe to say that the top-rated British chaser, Sprinter Sacre, will not be lining up in the Grand National whatever weight he would be allotted. Timeform argues, though, that if the chaser is to scale the heights he is potentially capable of, both with regards to his rating and his perception as one of the all-time greats, then a crack at the Cheltenham Gold Cup should be seriously considered.</p><p></p><p>\"Sprinter Sacre undoubtedly has the potential to secure a place for all time in the steeplechasing pantheon, though he might have to win a Cheltenham Gold Cup to truly capture the wider public's imagination. He will be untouchable if it is decided to confine him to the two-mile division, but he gives the distinct impression that anything is possible with him and he would start a short-priced favourite for the Gold Cup,\"says Timeform.</p><p></p><p><a href=\"http://www.racingpost.com/news/horse-racing/nicky-henderson-king-george-vi-not-on-agenda-for-sprinter-sacre/1524135/#newsArchiveTabs=last7DaysNews\" title=\"Racing Post\">The trainer Nicky Henderson has already ruled out the King George VI Chase for Sprinter Sacre</a> this season and the prospects of a Gold Cup bid are not promising at present, but Timeform points to the example of Flyingbolt.</p><p></p><p>The brilliant Irish chaser, as dominant as Sprinter Sacre is in the two-mile division, went on to put up even more meritorious performances at longer distances. Indeed, victory in the 1966 Irish Grand National under 12st 7lb, then run over the Gold Cup distance, was one of the performances that put him, in Timeform's estimation, within 2lb of the legendary Arkle.</p><p></p><p>Sprinter Sacre is currently rated the third highest ever National Hunt horse with the organisation at 192p (the letter denoting the possibility of improvement on that figure in Timeform's estimation). That rating is already 1lb above that of Mill House and, incidentally, Kauto Star, who, along with Desert Orchid, concurrently held the titles of best two-mile chaser and best staying chaser.</p><p></p><p>\"Arkle [212] and his great contemporary Flyingbolt [210] are the only horses to have earned a Timeform rating of over 200, a mark that Sprinter Sacre could probably achieve in the right circumstances,\" it argues.</p><p></p><p>The entry on Sprinter Sacre ends with a warning: \"Nothing should be taken for granted given the extent to which illness, injury and loss of form decimate the ranks of the top jumpers each season. Therefore, the advice to jumping devotees is to enjoy Sprinter Sacre while you can. It might be a long time before his like is seen again.\"</p><p></p><p>Justified complaints about the distances races are actually run over and ground descriptions – two factors in which accuracy is vital for punters – are made by Timeform in its essay on Captain Conan and it seems ludicrous that British racing is still failing in these two areas.</p><p></p><p>\"Races should always be staged over the exact [trip advertised] and, if starts cannot be moved [following the moving of rails on racecourses for example] to maintain those correct distances, then at the very least the BHA should insist that racecourses provide the public with completely accurate race distances when such changes are made (at the moment the distances of races over jumps are advertised to the nearest half furlong, which gives clerks of courses far too much leeway).</p><p></p><p>\"At the same time, the BHA should also take a much harder line with racecourses on going descriptions, the accuracy of which has arguably reached an all-time low at some tracks in recent seasons.\"</p><p></p><p>There are countless other topics discussed in the 1,000-plus pages covering the A–Z of the 9,000-plus runners that competed on Britain and Ireland's tracks last season, as well as analysis of the up-and-coming contenders for the championship crowns. As with last season, it is Sprinter Sacre and another of Henderson's runners, Simonsig (still, in Timeform's opinion, the biggest danger to his stable companion's dominance), the ratings experts are most looking forward to seeing.</p><p></p><p><em>Timeform's Chasers &amp; Hurdlers is published by Portway Press at £75.</em></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420003909|2013-10-17T12:52:59Z|d5a6f370d623d2291b3d8c62b099aad4d79588d3 -->",
