        "trailText":"Camelot was praised as 'the perfect racehorse' by Aidan O'Brien after sudden lameness forced his retirement",
        "headline":"Aidan O'Brien praises 'perfect' Camelot as lame Derby winner is retired",
        "body":"<p>Camelot, who almost became the first Triple Crown winner since 1970, ended his career in a downbeat manner on Monday, having retirement thrust upon him by lameness. The four-year-old will stand at Coolmore Stud from next year.</p><p>A statement from Coolmore said the injury was not serious but would keep him out of exercise for a week. In the circumstances connections were not minded to go through with a possible tilt at the Breeders' Cup Turf a fortnight on Saturday. Camelot had also figured in betting lists for the Champion Stakes at Ascot on Saturday but it appears this was no longer a target for him in any case.</p><p>Camelot was unbeaten in his first five races, including last year's 2,000 Guineas, Derby and Irish Derby, establishing a huge reputation. But his was a weak year and, remarkably, the six horses who were second or third behind him in those three Classics have all failed to win a single race since then.</p><p>Sent off at 2-5 for the final leg of the Triple Crown, the St Leger, Camelot was beaten three-quarters of a length by Encke. The winner has since been caught up in the Mahmood al-Zarooni doping scandal and tested positive for an anabolic steroid in spring, causing Camelot's connections to be the object of additional sympathy for that defeat.</p><p>Camelot won only one of his final five races and appeared to have his limitations exposed when twice beaten by Al Kazeem in the early part of this Flat season. His fans believe a  midwinter bout of colic may have robbed him of some of his ability.</p><p>\"He was the perfect racehorse,\" said his trainer, Aidan O'Brien, \"a beautiful horse with a terrific action. Unfortunately, we never saw the same brilliance on the racecourse as we had done before his colic operation but he was showing signs of it at home in recent weeks, so it's obviously disappointing that he won't get the opportunity to run again.\"</p><p>Later, at Limerick races, O'Brien all but ruled out Champions Day for two of his other horses, Declaration Of War and Magician, explaining that both want a sound surface, whereas the going at Ascot was soft in places even before 3.5mm of rain in the area on Monday. Declaration Of War would probably go straight to the Breeders' Cup Classic, he said.</p><p>\"Ruler Of The World and Kingsbarns are in [races on Champions Day] and both of those have form with ease in the ground, so maybe they'll run if the rain keeps coming as it is,\" O'Brien added. Both are entered in the Champion Stakes over 10 furlongs, while Kingsbarns also has the option of the QEII over a mile.</p><p>Fifteen horses were left in the Champion Stakes, which offers £1.3m in guaranteed prize money, at Monday's entry stage but, as Sky Lantern is another unlikely to be risked on soft going, it appears the race has a maximum of 12 potential runners. The going may also scupper the hoped-for fourth clash between Dawn Approach and Toronado in the QEII, as Toronado's connections also have Olympic Glory in the race and believe he would cope better with soft.</p><p>Reckless Abandon was another big name to be retired to stud. Clive Cox's colt was unbeaten in five runs as a juvenile last year, winning the Morny and the Middle Park, but could not add to those successes against top-class sprinters this year. He joins Sheikh Mohammed's Darley stud in Ireland.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419946260|2013-10-17T12:52:59Z|e695652840c674aa3e66cb119f4dba921925cabc -->",
