      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"8",
        "trailText":"Horse-racing pundit was dropped from Channel 4 to make way for sexier young female presenters, prosecution claims",
        "headline":"McCririck's antics 'pretty disgusting', television company boss tells tribunal",
        "body":"<p>A television company boss has described John McCririck's antics as \"pretty disgusting\", as he explained to a tribunal why the flamboyant betting pundit was dropped from Channel 4's racing coverage.</p><p>McCririck, 73, is suing Channel 4 and the TV production company IMG for alleged ageism after he was dropped in a revamp of the broadcaster's racing programmes.</p><p>But Graham Fry, managing director of sports production worldwide at IMG, said in a witness statement that McCririck was ditched because of concerns that his larger-than-life style grated with the public.</p><p>\"We were concerned that John McCririck's presenting style was over-dramatic, liable to offend and would not have mainstream appeal,\" he said.</p><p>\"I was also concerned about John McCririck's credibility as a betting presenter in the context of a more serious, journalistic style of Channel 4 Racing, given the public persona he had created through appearances on other television programmes.\"</p><p>Fry, who prepared IMG's winning bid to produce the programme, said he found McCririck's stints on reality shows \"pretty disgusting and shocking\".</p><p>Jennifer Eady QC, representing McCririck, challenged Fry about a message he wrote during the preparation of the bid which asked: \"Is there a sexier picture of Francesca Cumani we can put in?\"   Fry told the tribunal that it was a \"flippant comment to a colleague\" as he believed the presenter, suggested as a potential reporter for Channel 4 Racing but never used, looked \"quite severe\" in the initial picture.</p><p>Eady suggested it was evidence that IMG was really concerned with obtaining \"young, more glamorous, sexier presenters to appeal to the young audience\"  but Fry said the company was simply trying to identify new talent.</p><p>It also emerged that IMG considered using the supermodel Erin O'Connor for a fashion segment on the show.</p><p>\"We were looking for a look that appealed to a younger and broader audience, but we were always of the view that the most important thing was to get the best people and the best presenters as they would be the ones who could educate this younger and broader audience,\" said Fry.</p><p>In his witness statement he said McCririck's betting coverage was \"difficult to follow, since it was very technical and was delivered in a loud, brash, aggressive and long-winded style which I considered to be over the top and distracting\".</p><p>He described the Channel 4 Racing team, before the revamp, as having an exclusivity that resembled \"a country club environment\".</p><p>The tribunal has previously heard that all the companies that registered bids to make the 2013 Channel 4 Racing programme scaled back – or axed completely – McCririck from their pitches. The pundit, who is seeking £3m in damages and wants his job back, <a href=\"http://\" title=\"\">claims that his on-screen persona was encouraged by Channel 4 and that the sole reason for his sacking is his age. </a></p><p>The hearing continues.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418991114|2013-10-17T12:52:59Z|365032d989e6da7d12548ed4cbc280266f45a20c -->",
