      "id":"sport/2012/oct/21/ascot-crowds-cheer-frankel",
      "sectionId":"sport",
      "sectionName":"Sport",
      "webPublicationDate":"2012-10-20T23:23:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Ascot crowds cheer on Frankel as world's best ever horse exits to make £100m at stud",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/oct/21/ascot-crowds-cheer-frankel",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/sport/2012/oct/21/ascot-crowds-cheer-frankel",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"3",
        "trailText":"<p>Tim Lewis joins the Queen and packed grandstands in Berkshire to watch the stallion with star quality make history</p>",
        "headline":"Ascot crowds cheer on Frankel as world's best ever horse exits to make £100m at stud",
        "body":"<p>It was still dark when Sir Henry Cecil peered nervously out of the window on Saturday morning. When you've been in the game as long as he has, you develop a sense of what to expect, even before your eyes have time to adjust. There had been rain, but just a few spots, nothing to derail a day that he had been building up to for five decades – 43 years to be exact – of nurturing exceptional racehorses.</p><p>Yesterday afternoon, on damp, sludgy ground at Ascot (technically: \"soft, heavy in places\"), the 69-year-old Cecil watched the final race of Frankel, the once-in-a-lifetime thoroughbred he trains. There was excruciating tension – for Cecil, for the 32,000 sell-out crowd, for millions at home and in betting shops – but as usual Frankel was the coolest head on the course and streaked home to win by two lengths.</p><p>It is a mark of Frankel's dominance of Flat (as opposed to jump) racing that his greatest challenge was always going to be meteorological. Since his maiden run at Newmarket in August 2010, the four-year-old was unbeaten in 13 races coming into Ascot's Qipco Champion Stakes, and commonly thought to be unbeatable. The only question was how he would cope running a mile and a quarter through sodden turf, but no one was too surprised that his devastating finishing explosion – when each stride swallows 22ft and he tops 40mph – was gloriously unaffected.</p><p>Before the race, the horse – deep mahogany with a star on its forehead and four white socks – was expected to be challenged by the French gelding Cirrus Des Aigles, known to like the heavy stuff. But, after a poor start, he won almost without breaking sweat. As they entered the winner's enclosure, Frankel's jockey, Tom Queally, punched the air and roared with delight.</p><p>Their prize was £737,230, a share of the richest purse in British horseracing. This added to the £2,261,072 Frankel had already brought home for his owner Khalid Abdullah, a Saudi Arabian prince. Even these figures are mere oats and carrots compared with the riches that the colt will soon be earning for Prince Khalid in retirement, as the world's most desirable stallion. The exact stud fee has not been set yet but experts suggest it could be exorbitant. He would be expected to cover between 140 and 200 mares each year, leading to a valuation of £100m. Not bad, considering there is no guarantee that any offspring will inherit Frankel's obscene acceleration.</p><p>But the appeal of Frankel has never been about money. The reason Ascot was so rammed, the grandstands full with sharp suits and extravagant plumages on an overcast afternoon, was the chance to watch history. To say you had watched a horse who will now be mentioned in the same breath as Mill Reef and Dancing Brave. One spectator, Kelsey Padjen, had painted her nails in turquoise with a pink sash, to match Frankel's colours. The Queen came to see her horse Carlton House in an earlier race, but no doubt had half an eye on the main event.</p><p>\"Frankel's the most extraordinary horse I've seen,\" said the broadcaster Clare Balding, whose father had trained the great Mill Reef. \"What makes him so special is the efficiency of his stride, his power. But more than that, it's what he does inside you – how he wins races. He's so exciting, he makes the other horses look ordinary. He's what I call 'a jaw-dropper' – you watch him and your mouth falls open.\"</p><p>At the winning post yesterday, there was extra goodwill for Cecil, one of the most popular figures in British racing. In the mid-2000s, his career looked stuck in a downward spiral, as he struggled to cope with the death of his twin brother, the break-up of his second marriage and his heavy drinking. Then in 2006, he was diagnosed with non-Hodgkin lymphoma. He defeated that, but he is undergoing chemotherapy for another cancer, this time in his stomach. He looked frail in a three-piece suit and brown trilby yesterday on Saturday, but he is adamant that he has no plans to retire along with Frankel.</p><p>Last week, Cecil said: \"There will be a tear in my eye after his final race, because I don't expect to ever see another like him. But I can't quit, never. I have a family to support and feel I have a few more years left in me.\"</p><p>Even the bookies entered into the spirit yesterday. In a natty pinstripe blazer, Big Jim, from Betting With Big Jim, attempted to lure punters by saying that he would pay out as if Frankel was not in the race – that is, it was a foregone conclusion who would win, so this would at least keep it interesting. \"Better rates than you'd get at RBS,\" he promised. \"More guaranteed than RBS, too!\"</p><p>\"Every sport needs heroes, and that's what Frankel is,\" said Big Jim. \"He's not been great for the bookies, to be honest, but he's brilliant to watch. We're going to miss him.\"</p><p>In fact, Frankel has been so much better than his rivals that neither punters nor bookies have profited much from his success. After all, where's the gamble if you know who is going to win? He has been odds-on in all his races, apart from his debut: if you had staked £1 on each of his 13 victories, you would have been just £5.78 richer. For the Qipco Champion Stakes his odds were a miserly 2-11. For the casual flutterer, the winnings would not even cover the petrol to the betting shop.</p><p>There was another farewell yesterday as the BBC ended its association with Flat racing and Ascot, a relationship that goes back 61 years. For the next four years at least, all the major meetings – including the Grand National, the Derby, Royal Ascot and the Cheltenham Festival – will be screened on Channel 4. It would have been a small consolation for the corporation that the BBC era ended at the same time as the career of the greatest Flat racehorse of our times.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/398107649|2013-10-17T12:52:59Z|cca8cf3a451e5117fdbb486ebef293e4ad8bff32 -->",
